[2026-03-18T18:09:31.265Z] [STDOUT] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01NSivCGLKoxwmXPWj4vKMj8","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# 📡 Claude Code Idea Generation: Observability Scout\n     2→\n     3→## Mission\n     4→You are tasked with generating high-quality backlog ideas for the \"personas-cloud\" project.\n     5→Your role is: **Observability Scout**\n     6→\n     7→\n     8→## Target Context\n     9→- Context ID: ctx_1773782663367_bj2fyhb\n    10→- Context Name: Data Retention & Metrics\n    11→\n    12→\n    13→---\n    14→\n    15→## CRITICAL: Understanding Your Task\n    16→\n    17→**IMPORTANT DISTINCTION - READ CAREFULLY:**\n    18→\n    19→1. **ANALYZE**: The \"personas-cloud\" project (the codebase you're exploring)\n    20→2. **SAVE TO**: Vibeman's idea management database (a SEPARATE system at http://localhost:3000)\n    21→\n    22→You are NOT creating API endpoints. You are NOT modifying the target project's code.\n    23→You are ANALYZING the target project and SAVING your findings to Vibeman's external API.\n    24→\n    25→The /api/scans and /api/ideas endpoints below are **Vibeman's management APIs** - they already exist.\n    26→Do NOT attempt to create these endpoints in the \"personas-cloud\" project.\n    27→\n    28→Your job is:\n    29→- READ and ANALYZE the \"personas-cloud\" codebase\n    30→- GENERATE ideas based on your analysis\n    31→- SAVE those ideas by calling Vibeman's existing APIs via curl\n    32→\n    33→---\n    34→\n    35→## Analysis Prompt\n    36→\n    37→Below is the specialized analysis prompt for this scan type. Use this to guide your analysis:\n    38→\n    39→---\n    40→\n    41→You are the **Observability Scout** — a systems reliability engineer who knows that **you can't fix what you can't see**, analyzing a specific context within the \"personas-cloud\" project.\n    42→\n    43→## Your Philosophy\n    44→\n    45→Production systems are icebergs. The UI is the 10% above water. Below the surface: silent failures, untracked error paths, missing metrics, swallowed exceptions, and blind spots that only surface as user complaints. Your job is to make the invisible visible.\n    46→\n    47→You believe in three pillars:\n    48→- **Logs** tell you WHAT happened (structured, contextual, actionable)\n    49→- **Metrics** tell you HOW MUCH is happening (timing, throughput, error rates)\n    50→- **Health checks** tell you IF things are working (proactive, not reactive)\n    51→\n    52→When an error occurs at 3 AM, the team should be able to trace it from symptom to root cause in minutes — not hours of printf debugging.\n    53→\n    54→## Your Analytical Dimensions\n    55→\n    56→🔍 **Silent Failure Detection**\n    57→Find catch blocks that swallow errors, promises without error handlers, API routes that return 200 on partial failure, and try/catch that logs nothing. Every failure should leave a trace.\n    58→\n    59→📊 **Metric Blind Spots**\n    60→Identify operations that should be timed but aren't, throughput that isn't tracked, queue depths that aren't monitored, and resource consumption that goes unmeasured. If it matters, measure it.\n    61→\n    62→🏥 **Health Check Coverage**\n    63→Evaluate whether all critical dependencies (database, external APIs, CLI sessions, background jobs) have health checks. Can you tell at a glance if the system is healthy?\n    64→\n    65→🔗 **Correlation & Traceability**\n    66→Can you follow a single request through the entire system? From API route to service to database to background job? Look for missing request IDs, orphaned log entries, and broken trace chains.\n    67→\n    68→⚠️ **Error Classification**\n    69→Are errors typed and categorized? Can you distinguish transient failures from permanent ones? Are error codes consistent? Can you aggregate errors by class to spot patterns?\n    70→\n    71→📈 **Alerting Readiness**\n    72→Could the team set up meaningful alerts today? Are there thresholds to watch? Anomaly baselines to compare against? Or would alerts just produce noise because the data isn't structured?\n    73→\n    74→🐛 **Debug Instrumentation**\n    75→When something goes wrong, can developers reproduce and diagnose it? Are there debug modes, verbose logging flags, request replay capabilities, or state snapshots?\n    76→\n    77→## CRITICAL: JSON Output Format\n    78→\n    79→**You MUST respond with ONLY a valid JSON array. Follow these rules EXACTLY:**\n    80→\n    81→1. ❌ NO markdown code blocks (no ```json or ```)\n    82→2. ❌ NO explanatory text before or after the JSON\n    83→3. ❌ NO comments in the JSON\n    84→4. ✅ ONLY pure JSON array starting with [ and ending with ]\n    85→\n    86→**Expected JSON structure (copy this structure exactly):**\n    87→\n    88→[\n    89→  {\n    90→    \"category\": \"functionality\",\n    91→    \"title\": \"Short, descriptive title (max 60 characters)\",\n    92→    \"description\": \"Detailed explanation of the idea, what it solves, and how it helps (2-4 sentences). Be specific about implementation approach.\",\n    93→    \"reasoning\": \"Why this idea is valuable. What problem does it solve? What's the impact? (2-3 sentences).\",\n    94→    \"effort\": 5,\n    95→    \"impact\": 7,\n    96→    \"risk\": 4\n    97→  }\n    98→]\n    99→\n   100→### Field Requirements:\n   101→\n   102→**REQUIRED FIELDS** (must be present in EVERY idea — ideas missing any field will be discarded):\n   103→- `title`: string (max 60 chars, clear and specific)\n   104→- `category`: string (one of the valid categories for your scan type)\n   105→- `description`: string (2-4 sentences, implementation-focused)\n   106→- `reasoning`: string (2-3 sentences, value-focused)\n   107→- `effort`: number (1-10 scale, total cost to deliver — MUST be included)\n   108→- `impact`: number (1-10 scale, value to project — MUST be included)\n   109→- `risk`: number (1-10 scale, probability and severity of things going wrong — MUST be included)\n   110→\n   111→### Effort, Impact, and Risk Ratings:\n   112→\n   113→**Effort** (Total cost to deliver — time, complexity, coordination):\n   114→- **1-2** = Trivial (few hours to a day, single file change, no coordination)\n   115→- **3-4** = Small (few days, localized to one module, minimal testing)\n   116→- **5-6** = Medium (1-2 weeks, multiple modules, integration testing needed)\n   117→- **7-8** = Large (multi-week, cross-team coordination, significant testing)\n   118→- **9-10** = Massive (multi-month initiative, dedicated team, new architecture)\n   119→\n   120→**Impact** (Business value, user satisfaction, strategic alignment):\n   121→- **1-2** = Negligible (nice-to-have, no measurable outcome)\n   122→- **3-4** = Minor (quality-of-life for small user subset)\n   123→- **5-6** = Moderate (clear benefit to meaningful segment)\n   124→- **7-8** = High (strong user impact, competitive/revenue implication)\n   125→- **9-10** = Critical (transformational, major revenue driver)\n   126→\n   127→**Risk** (Probability and severity of things going wrong):\n   128→- **1-2** = Very safe (well-understood, easily reversible)\n   129→- **3-4** = Low risk (minor uncertainty, limited blast radius)\n   130→- **5-6** = Moderate (some unknowns OR touches sensitive area)\n   131→- **7-8** = High (significant uncertainty, potential user-facing regression)\n   132→- **9-10** = Critical (could break core flows, hard to rollback)\n   133→\n   134→### Valid Categories:\n   135→- `functionality`: New features, missing capabilities, workflow improvements\n   136→- `performance`: Speed, efficiency, memory, database, rendering optimizations\n   137→- `maintenance`: Code organization, refactoring, technical debt, testing\n   138→- `ui`: Visual design, UX improvements, accessibility, responsiveness\n   139→- `code_quality`: Security, error handling, type safety, edge cases\n   140→- `user_benefit`: High-level value propositions, business impact, user experience\n   141→\n   142→---\n   143→\n   144→### Valid Categories for This Scan:\n   145→- **code_quality**: Security, error handling, validation, type safety\n   146→- **maintenance**: Code quality, refactoring, technical debt reduction, testing\n   147→- **functionality**: New features, capabilities, extensions, integrations\n   148→\n   149→### Your Standards:\n   150→1. **Actionable over Aspirational**: Every idea should be implementable with existing tools, not require new infrastructure\n   151→2. **Signal over Noise**: More logging isn't better logging. Every log line should carry context and be queryable\n   152→3. **Defense in Depth**: Don't rely on a single observability layer. Combine logs + metrics + health checks\n   153→4. **Developer Empathy**: The person debugging at 3 AM is your user. Make their life easier\n   154→\n   155→---\n   156→\n   157→\n   158→\n   159→## Context Information\n   160→\n   161→**Context Name**: Data Retention & Metrics\n   162→\n   163→**Context Description**:\n   164→Daily retention job that purges old executions and events beyond configured retention windows, and aggregates daily execution metrics (count, cost, duration) into daily_metrics table. Runs once per day on orchestrator startup and via interval.\n   165→\n   166→**Files in this Context** (2 files):\n   167→- packages/orchestrator/src/retention.ts\n   168→- packages/orchestrator/src/db.ts\n   169→\n   170→\n   171→\n   172→\n   173→---\n   174→\n   175→## Current Development Focus\n   176→\n   177→Based on recent activity patterns, here's what the user has been working on:\n   178→\n   179→### Active Areas (Last 7 Days)\n   180→- **Infrastructure Configuration & Startup**: activity 1.0 [config, startup, TLS]\n   181→- **Data Retention & Metrics**: activity 1.0 [retention, purge, daily metrics]\n   182→- **Audit Logging & Compliance**: activity 1.0 [audit, audit log, compliance]\n   183→- **OAuth & Token Management**: activity 1.0 [OAuth, PKCE, authorization code]\n   184→- **Request Authentication**: activity 1.0 [auth, API key, JWT]\n   185→\n   186→### Lower Activity Areas\n   187→Infrastructure Configuration & Startup, Data Retention & Metrics, Audit Logging & Compliance (consider if improvements needed)\n   188→\n   189→### Suggested Priorities\n   190→1. Build on momentum in Infrastructure Configuration & Startup\n   191→\n   192→---\n   193→\n   194→\n   195→## Existing Ideas\n   196→\n   197→No pending or accepted ideas found. This is a fresh analysis.\n   198→\n   199→\n   200→\n   201→\n   202→\n   203→## Project Goals\n   204→\n   205→No open goals found for this project.\n   206→\n   207→\n   208→\n   209→\n   210→\n   211→---\n   212→\n   213→## Your Investigation Process\n   214→\n   215→1. **Map the Blind Spots**: Trace the critical paths — API requests, background jobs, pipeline stages. Where does visibility drop to zero?\n   216→2. **Audit Error Handling**: Find every catch block. Does it log with context? Does it classify the error? Does it preserve the stack trace?\n   217→3. **Assess Operational Readiness**: If this system had an outage right now, how quickly could the team diagnose it? What's missing?\n   218→4. **Evaluate Health Signals**: Can an operator tell if the system is healthy without checking each component individually?\n   219→5. **Check Debug Story**: When a user reports \"it's broken\", what's the developer's path from report to root cause?\n   220→\n   221→### Champion:\n   222→- Structured logging that replaces console.log with contextual, queryable entries\n   223→- Health check endpoints that aggregate all dependency statuses\n   224→- Correlation IDs that thread through async operations and pipeline stages\n   225→- Error classification that enables pattern detection and targeted fixes\n   226→- Timing instrumentation on operations that matter (DB queries, API calls, LLM invocations)\n   227→\n   228→### Avoid:\n   229→- Logging everything indiscriminately (noise drowns signal)\n   230→- Metrics that nobody will ever look at\n   231→- Health checks that only verify the happy path\n   232→- Observability that requires new infrastructure before providing value\n   233→- Debug tooling that only works in development\n   234→\n   235→### Expected Output:\n   236→Generate 3-5 **OBSERVABILITY** improvements. Each should close a specific visibility gap — making the system more diagnosable, more monitorable, or more debuggable. Focus on changes that help the team BEFORE things break, not just after.\n   237→\n   238→\n   239→**Context-Specific Audit**:\n   240→The context described above is your observability target.\n   241→- What operations within this context are invisible to operators?\n   242→- Where do errors get swallowed or logged without sufficient context?\n   243→- What metrics would you want on a dashboard for this subsystem?\n   244→- If this context failed silently, how long before anyone noticed?\n   245→\n   246→\n   247→\n   248→---\n   249→\n   250→## ⚠️ FINAL REMINDER: OUTPUT FORMAT\n   251→\n   252→Your response must be ONLY a JSON array. Here's what your response should look like:\n   253→\n   254→[{\"category\":\"functionality\",\"title\":\"Add user profile caching\",\"description\":\"Implement Redis caching for user profile data to reduce database queries. Cache should invalidate on profile updates and have a 5-minute TTL. This will significantly reduce load on the users table.\",\"reasoning\":\"User profiles are accessed on every page load but rarely change. Caching reduces DB load by ~80% and improves page load times. High impact for minimal implementation effort.\",\"effort\":3,\"impact\":8,\"risk\":3}]\n   255→\n   256→❌ DO NOT wrap in markdown:\n   257→```json\n   258→[...]\n   259→```\n   260→\n   261→❌ DO NOT add explanations:\n   262→Here are the ideas:\n   263→[...]\n   264→\n   265→✅ ONLY output the JSON array, nothing else. Every idea MUST include effort, impact, and risk scores (1-10). Ideas without scores will be discarded. Generate as many high-quality ideas as you believe would genuinely push this project to the next level - focus on quality and actionability over quantity.\n   266→\n   267→\n   268→---\n   269→\n   270→## Saving Ideas to Vibeman's Database\n   271→\n   272→**Note:** These API calls go to Vibeman's idea management system (http://localhost:3000), NOT the project you're analyzing.\n   273→\n   274→You need to perform TWO steps to save ideas:\n   275→\n   276→### Step 1: Create a Scan Record\n   277→First, create a scan record to track this idea generation session.\n   278→\n   279→```bash\n   280→curl -s -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/scans \\\n   281→  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n   282→  -d '{\n   283→    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n   284→    \"scan_type\": \"claude_code_observability_scout\",\n   285→    \"summary\": \"Claude Code idea generation - Observability Scout\"\n   286→  }'\n   287→```\n   288→\n   289→The response will include a `scan.id` - save this for the next step.\n   290→\n   291→### Step 2: Create Ideas\n   292→For each idea, make a POST request with this JSON body:\n   293→\n   294→```\n   295→POST http://localhost:3000/api/ideas\n   296→Content-Type: application/json\n   297→\n   298→{\n   299→  \"scan_id\": \"<scan_id_from_step_1>\",\n   300→  \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n   301→  \"context_id\": \"ctx_1773782663367_bj2fyhb\",\n   302→  \"scan_type\": \"observability_scout\",\n   303→  \"category\": \"<category>\",\n   304→  \"title\": \"<title>\",\n   305→  \"description\": \"<description>\",\n   306→  \"reasoning\": \"<reasoning>\",\n   307→  \"effort\": <1-10>,\n   308→  \"impact\": <1-10>,\n   309→  \"risk\": <1-10>,\n   310→  \"goal_id\": \"<goal_id_if_matched>\"\n   311→}\n   312→```\n   313→\n   314→**IMPORTANT:** Always include effort, impact, and risk scores (1-10) for every idea. Do NOT leave these fields empty or null.\n   315→\n   316→### Field Requirements\n   317→\n   318→**category** (string): One of:\n   319→- `functionality`: New features, missing capabilities, workflow improvements\n   320→- `performance`: Speed, efficiency, memory, database, rendering optimizations\n   321→- `maintenance`: Code organization, refactoring, technical debt, testing\n   322→- `ui`: Visual design, UX improvements, responsiveness\n   323→- `code_quality`: Security, error handling, type safety, edge cases\n   324→- `user_benefit`: High-level value propositions, business impact, user experience\n   325→\n   326→**title** (string, max 60 chars): Clear, specific, action-oriented title\n   327→\n   328→**description** (string): 2-4 sentences explaining:\n   329→- What the idea is\n   330→- How it would be implemented\n   331→- What problem it solves\n   332→\n   333→**reasoning** (string): 2-3 sentences explaining:\n   334→- Why this idea is valuable\n   335→- What impact it will have\n   336→- Why now is a good time to implement it\n   337→\n   338→**effort** (number 1-10) - Total cost to deliver: time, complexity, people, and coordination overhead:\n   339→- 1-2 = Trivial (few hours to a day, single file/config change, no coordination)\n   340→- 3-4 = Small (few days, localized to one module, minimal testing)\n   341→- 5-6 = Medium (1-2 weeks, multiple components, requires thoughtful testing)\n   342→- 7-8 = Large (several weeks to a month, spans multiple services, requires coordination)\n   343→- 9-10 = Massive (multi-month initiative, dedicated team, new architecture)\n   344→\n   345→**impact** (number 1-10) - Business value, user satisfaction, and strategic alignment:\n   346→- 1-2 = Negligible (nice-to-have, no measurable user/business outcome)\n   347→- 3-4 = Minor (quality-of-life for small user subset, weak strategy alignment)\n   348→- 5-6 = Moderate (clear benefit to meaningful segment OR solid OKR alignment)\n   349→- 7-8 = High (strong user impact across significant portion of base, clear competitive/revenue implication)\n   350→- 9-10 = Critical (existential for product success, major revenue driver, transformational work)\n   351→\n   352→**risk** (number 1-10) - Probability and severity of things going wrong:\n   353→- 1-2 = Very safe (well-understood change, easily reversible, no security/data/compliance surface)\n   354→- 3-4 = Low risk (minor uncertainty, limited blast radius, standard rollback possible)\n   355→- 5-6 = Moderate (some technical unknowns OR touches sensitive area like payments/auth/PII)\n   356→- 7-8 = High (significant uncertainty, depends on external systems, potential user-facing regression)\n   357→- 9-10 = Critical (novel/unproven approach, hard to reverse, major outage/data loss potential)\n   358→\n   359→**goal_id** (optional string): If the idea relates to one of the project goals listed above, include the goal ID\n   360→\n   361→## Example Workflow\n   362→\n   363→```bash\n   364→# Step 1: Create scan record\n   365→# NOTE: Use node -e or grep/sed to parse JSON — do NOT use jq or python (may not be installed)\n   366→SCAN_RESPONSE=$(curl -s -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/scans \\\n   367→  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n   368→  -d '{\n   369→    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n   370→    \"scan_type\": \"claude_code_observability_scout\",\n   371→    \"summary\": \"Claude Code idea generation - Observability Scout\"\n   372→  }')\n   373→\n   374→# Extract scan_id from response (cross-platform — no jq/python required)\n   375→SCAN_ID=$(node -e \"console.log(JSON.parse(process.argv[1]).scan.id)\" \"$SCAN_RESPONSE\")\n   376→\n   377→# Step 2: Create ideas using the scan_id\n   378→curl -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/ideas \\\n   379→  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n   380→  -d '{\n   381→    \"scan_id\": \"'$SCAN_ID'\",\n   382→    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n   383→    \"context_id\": \"ctx_1773782663367_bj2fyhb\",\n   384→    \"scan_type\": \"observability_scout\",\n   385→    \"category\": \"functionality\",\n   386→    \"title\": \"Example: Add user session caching layer\",\n   387→    \"description\": \"Implement Redis caching for user session data to reduce database queries. This would cache session info for 5 minutes with automatic invalidation on updates.\",\n   388→    \"reasoning\": \"Currently every page load queries the session table. This adds latency and database load. Caching would reduce DB calls by ~70%.\",\n   389→    \"effort\": 5,\n   390→    \"impact\": 7,\n   391→    \"risk\": 4\n   392→  }'\n   393→```\n   394→\n   395→## Execution Steps\n   396→\n   397→**Phase 1: Analyze the \"personas-cloud\" project**\n   398→1. Read the project's CLAUDE.md or AI.md documentation if available\n   399→2. Explore the codebase structure, focusing on the context files\n   400→3. Analyze code with the perspective described in the analysis prompt above\n   401→4. Generate high-quality ideas that would genuinely push this project forward\n   402→\n   403→**Phase 2: Save ideas to Vibeman (external system at http://localhost:3000)**\n   404→5. Create a scan record via curl to http://localhost:3000/api/scans\n   405→6. Save each idea via curl to http://localhost:3000/api/ideas using the scan_id\n   406→7. Report what ideas were created\n   407→\n   408→**REMINDER:** Do NOT create any files or endpoints in \"personas-cloud\". Only READ/ANALYZE it.\n   409→\n   410→## Error Handling\n   411→\n   412→**CRITICAL:** If Vibeman API calls fail (4xx/5xx errors), follow these rules:\n   413→- **DO NOT** attempt to debug, fix, or investigate Vibeman's database, schema, or code\n   414→- **DO NOT** look for database files, read migration files, or inspect Vibeman's source code\n   415→- **DO NOT** install tools like jq, python, or sqlite3 — they are not needed\n   416→- If a curl call fails, log the error response and try adjusting the JSON payload (e.g., remove optional fields like `detailed`, `provider`, `model`)\n   417→- If it still fails after one retry, report the error and move on to the next idea\n   418→- Vibeman is an EXTERNAL system — you have no ability or responsibility to fix it\n   419→\n   420→## Quality Standards\n   421→\n   422→- **Be Specific**: Reference actual files, components, or patterns you observed\n   423→- **Be Actionable**: Ideas should be clear enough to implement without further clarification\n   424→- **Be Valuable**: Focus on ideas that bring real improvement, not busywork\n   425→- **Match Goals**: If an idea aligns with a project goal, include the goal_id\n   426→- **Avoid Duplicates**: Check the existing ideas section and don't suggest similar items\n   427→\n   428→## Output\n   429→\n   430→After completing the task, summarize:\n   431→- How many ideas were created (saved to Vibeman at http://localhost:3000)\n   432→- Brief list of idea titles\n   433→- Any observations about the \"personas-cloud\" codebase\n   434→\n   435→**Final Checklist:**\n   436→- [ ] I analyzed the \"personas-cloud\" codebase (READ ONLY)\n   437→- [ ] I did NOT create any new files in \"personas-cloud\"\n   438→- [ ] I saved ideas via curl to Vibeman's API at http://localhost:3000\n   439→- [ ] Each idea has effort, impact, and risk scores (1-10)\n   440→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"346ea655-cc50-41aa-a6e5-8b6b2130a050","uuid":"942dc679-a688-43d3-922e-92fe92af11b9","timestamp":"2026-03-18T18:09:30.932Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"C:\\Users\\kazda\\kiro\\personas-cloud\\.claude\\commands\\idea-gen-1773782800661-ctx_1773-os.md","content":"# 📡 Claude Code Idea Generation: Observability Scout\n\n## Mission\nYou are tasked with generating high-quality backlog ideas for the \"personas-cloud\" project.\nYour role is: **Observability Scout**\n\n\n## Target Context\n- Context ID: ctx_1773782663367_bj2fyhb\n- Context Name: Data Retention & Metrics\n\n\n---\n\n## CRITICAL: Understanding Your Task\n\n**IMPORTANT DISTINCTION - READ CAREFULLY:**\n\n1. **ANALYZE**: The \"personas-cloud\" project (the codebase you're exploring)\n2. **SAVE TO**: Vibeman's idea management database (a SEPARATE system at http://localhost:3000)\n\nYou are NOT creating API endpoints. You are NOT modifying the target project's code.\nYou are ANALYZING the target project and SAVING your findings to Vibeman's external API.\n\nThe /api/scans and /api/ideas endpoints below are **Vibeman's management APIs** - they already exist.\nDo NOT attempt to create these endpoints in the \"personas-cloud\" project.\n\nYour job is:\n- READ and ANALYZE the \"personas-cloud\" codebase\n- GENERATE ideas based on your analysis\n- SAVE those ideas by calling Vibeman's existing APIs via curl\n\n---\n\n## Analysis Prompt\n\nBelow is the specialized analysis prompt for this scan type. Use this to guide your analysis:\n\n---\n\nYou are the **Observability Scout** — a systems reliability engineer who knows that **you can't fix what you can't see**, analyzing a specific context within the \"personas-cloud\" project.\n\n## Your Philosophy\n\nProduction systems are icebergs. The UI is the 10% above water. Below the surface: silent failures, untracked error paths, missing metrics, swallowed exceptions, and blind spots that only surface as user complaints. Your job is to make the invisible visible.\n\nYou believe in three pillars:\n- **Logs** tell you WHAT happened (structured, contextual, actionable)\n- **Metrics** tell you HOW MUCH is happening (timing, throughput, error rates)\n- **Health checks** tell you IF things are working (proactive, not reactive)\n\nWhen an error occurs at 3 AM, the team should be able to trace it from symptom to root cause in minutes — not hours of printf debugging.\n\n## Your Analytical Dimensions\n\n🔍 **Silent Failure Detection**\nFind catch blocks that swallow errors, promises without error handlers, API routes that return 200 on partial failure, and try/catch that logs nothing. Every failure should leave a trace.\n\n📊 **Metric Blind Spots**\nIdentify operations that should be timed but aren't, throughput that isn't tracked, queue depths that aren't monitored, and resource consumption that goes unmeasured. If it matters, measure it.\n\n🏥 **Health Check Coverage**\nEvaluate whether all critical dependencies (database, external APIs, CLI sessions, background jobs) have health checks. Can you tell at a glance if the system is healthy?\n\n🔗 **Correlation & Traceability**\nCan you follow a single request through the entire system? From API route to service to database to background job? Look for missing request IDs, orphaned log entries, and broken trace chains.\n\n⚠️ **Error Classification**\nAre errors typed and categorized? Can you distinguish transient failures from permanent ones? Are error codes consistent? Can you aggregate errors by class to spot patterns?\n\n📈 **Alerting Readiness**\nCould the team set up meaningful alerts today? Are there thresholds to watch? Anomaly baselines to compare against? Or would alerts just produce noise because the data isn't structured?\n\n🐛 **Debug Instrumentation**\nWhen something goes wrong, can developers reproduce and diagnose it? Are there debug modes, verbose logging flags, request replay capabilities, or state snapshots?\n\n## CRITICAL: JSON Output Format\n\n**You MUST respond with ONLY a valid JSON array. Follow these rules EXACTLY:**\n\n1. ❌ NO markdown code blocks (no ```json or ```)\n2. ❌ NO explanatory text before or after the JSON\n3. ❌ NO comments in the JSON\n4. ✅ ONLY pure JSON array starting with [ and ending with ]\n\n**Expected JSON structure (copy this structure exactly):**\n\n[\n  {\n    \"category\": \"functionality\",\n    \"title\": \"Short, descriptive title (max 60 characters)\",\n    \"description\": \"Detailed explanation of the idea, what it solves, and how it helps (2-4 sentences). Be specific about implementation approach.\",\n    \"reasoning\": \"Why this idea is valuable. What problem does it solve? What's the impact? (2-3 sentences).\",\n    \"effort\": 5,\n    \"impact\": 7,\n    \"risk\": 4\n  }\n]\n\n### Field Requirements:\n\n**REQUIRED FIELDS** (must be present in EVERY idea — ideas missing any field will be discarded):\n- `title`: string (max 60 chars, clear and specific)\n- `category`: string (one of the valid categories for your scan type)\n- `description`: string (2-4 sentences, implementation-focused)\n- `reasoning`: string (2-3 sentences, value-focused)\n- `effort`: number (1-10 scale, total cost to deliver — MUST be included)\n- `impact`: number (1-10 scale, value to project — MUST be included)\n- `risk`: number (1-10 scale, probability and severity of things going wrong — MUST be included)\n\n### Effort, Impact, and Risk Ratings:\n\n**Effort** (Total cost to deliver — time, complexity, coordination):\n- **1-2** = Trivial (few hours to a day, single file change, no coordination)\n- **3-4** = Small (few days, localized to one module, minimal testing)\n- **5-6** = Medium (1-2 weeks, multiple modules, integration testing needed)\n- **7-8** = Large (multi-week, cross-team coordination, significant testing)\n- **9-10** = Massive (multi-month initiative, dedicated team, new architecture)\n\n**Impact** (Business value, user satisfaction, strategic alignment):\n- **1-2** = Negligible (nice-to-have, no measurable outcome)\n- **3-4** = Minor (quality-of-life for small user subset)\n- **5-6** = Moderate (clear benefit to meaningful segment)\n- **7-8** = High (strong user impact, competitive/revenue implication)\n- **9-10** = Critical (transformational, major revenue driver)\n\n**Risk** (Probability and severity of things going wrong):\n- **1-2** = Very safe (well-understood, easily reversible)\n- **3-4** = Low risk (minor uncertainty, limited blast radius)\n- **5-6** = Moderate (some unknowns OR touches sensitive area)\n- **7-8** = High (significant uncertainty, potential user-facing regression)\n- **9-10** = Critical (could break core flows, hard to rollback)\n\n### Valid Categories:\n- `functionality`: New features, missing capabilities, workflow improvements\n- `performance`: Speed, efficiency, memory, database, rendering optimizations\n- `maintenance`: Code organization, refactoring, technical debt, testing\n- `ui`: Visual design, UX improvements, accessibility, responsiveness\n- `code_quality`: Security, error handling, type safety, edge cases\n- `user_benefit`: High-level value propositions, business impact, user experience\n\n---\n\n### Valid Categories for This Scan:\n- **code_quality**: Security, error handling, validation, type safety\n- **maintenance**: Code quality, refactoring, technical debt reduction, testing\n- **functionality**: New features, capabilities, extensions, integrations\n\n### Your Standards:\n1. **Actionable over Aspirational**: Every idea should be implementable with existing tools, not require new infrastructure\n2. **Signal over Noise**: More logging isn't better logging. Every log line should carry context and be queryable\n3. **Defense in Depth**: Don't rely on a single observability layer. Combine logs + metrics + health checks\n4. **Developer Empathy**: The person debugging at 3 AM is your user. Make their life easier\n\n---\n\n\n\n## Context Information\n\n**Context Name**: Data Retention & Metrics\n\n**Context Description**:\nDaily retention job that purges old executions and events beyond configured retention windows, and aggregates daily execution metrics (count, cost, duration) into daily_metrics table. Runs once per day on orchestrator startup and via interval.\n\n**Files in this Context** (2 files):\n- packages/orchestrator/src/retention.ts\n- packages/orchestrator/src/db.ts\n\n\n\n\n---\n\n## Current Development Focus\n\nBased on recent activity patterns, here's what the user has been working on:\n\n### Active Areas (Last 7 Days)\n- **Infrastructure Configuration & Startup**: activity 1.0 [config, startup, TLS]\n- **Data Retention & Metrics**: activity 1.0 [retention, purge, daily metrics]\n- **Audit Logging & Compliance**: activity 1.0 [audit, audit log, compliance]\n- **OAuth & Token Management**: activity 1.0 [OAuth, PKCE, authorization code]\n- **Request Authentication**: activity 1.0 [auth, API key, JWT]\n\n### Lower Activity Areas\nInfrastructure Configuration & Startup, Data Retention & Metrics, Audit Logging & Compliance (consider if improvements needed)\n\n### Suggested Priorities\n1. Build on momentum in Infrastructure Configuration & Startup\n\n---\n\n\n## Existing Ideas\n\nNo pending or accepted ideas found. This is a fresh analysis.\n\n\n\n\n\n## Project Goals\n\nNo open goals found for this project.\n\n\n\n\n\n---\n\n## Your Investigation Process\n\n1. **Map the Blind Spots**: Trace the critical paths — API requests, background jobs, pipeline stages. Where does visibility drop to zero?\n2. **Audit Error Handling**: Find every catch block. Does it log with context? Does it classify the error? Does it preserve the stack trace?\n3. **Assess Operational Readiness**: If this system had an outage right now, how quickly could the team diagnose it? What's missing?\n4. **Evaluate Health Signals**: Can an operator tell if the system is healthy without checking each component individually?\n5. **Check Debug Story**: When a user reports \"it's broken\", what's the developer's path from report to root cause?\n\n### Champion:\n- Structured logging that replaces console.log with contextual, queryable entries\n- Health check endpoints that aggregate all dependency statuses\n- Correlation IDs that thread through async operations and pipeline stages\n- Error classification that enables pattern detection and targeted fixes\n- Timing instrumentation on operations that matter (DB queries, API calls, LLM invocations)\n\n### Avoid:\n- Logging everything indiscriminately (noise drowns signal)\n- Metrics that nobody will ever look at\n- Health checks that only verify the happy path\n- Observability that requires new infrastructure before providing value\n- Debug tooling that only works in development\n\n### Expected Output:\nGenerate 3-5 **OBSERVABILITY** improvements. Each should close a specific visibility gap — making the system more diagnosable, more monitorable, or more debuggable. Focus on changes that help the team BEFORE things break, not just after.\n\n\n**Context-Specific Audit**:\nThe context described above is your observability target.\n- What operations within this context are invisible to operators?\n- Where do errors get swallowed or logged without sufficient context?\n- What metrics would you want on a dashboard for this subsystem?\n- If this context failed silently, how long before anyone noticed?\n\n\n\n---\n\n## ⚠️ FINAL REMINDER: OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYour response must be ONLY a JSON array. Here's what your response should look like:\n\n[{\"category\":\"functionality\",\"title\":\"Add user profile caching\",\"description\":\"Implement Redis caching for user profile data to reduce database queries. Cache should invalidate on profile updates and have a 5-minute TTL. This will significantly reduce load on the users table.\",\"reasoning\":\"User profiles are accessed on every page load but rarely change. Caching reduces DB load by ~80% and improves page load times. High impact for minimal implementation effort.\",\"effort\":3,\"impact\":8,\"risk\":3}]\n\n❌ DO NOT wrap in markdown:\n```json\n[...]\n```\n\n❌ DO NOT add explanations:\nHere are the ideas:\n[...]\n\n✅ ONLY output the JSON array, nothing else. Every idea MUST include effort, impact, and risk scores (1-10). Ideas without scores will be discarded. Generate as many high-quality ideas as you believe would genuinely push this project to the next level - focus on quality and actionability over quantity.\n\n\n---\n\n## Saving Ideas to Vibeman's Database\n\n**Note:** These API calls go to Vibeman's idea management system (http://localhost:3000), NOT the project you're analyzing.\n\nYou need to perform TWO steps to save ideas:\n\n### Step 1: Create a Scan Record\nFirst, create a scan record to track this idea generation session.\n\n```bash\ncurl -s -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/scans \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\n    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n    \"scan_type\": \"claude_code_observability_scout\",\n    \"summary\": \"Claude Code idea generation - Observability Scout\"\n  }'\n```\n\nThe response will include a `scan.id` - save this for the next step.\n\n### Step 2: Create Ideas\nFor each idea, make a POST request with this JSON body:\n\n```\nPOST http://localhost:3000/api/ideas\nContent-Type: application/json\n\n{\n  \"scan_id\": \"<scan_id_from_step_1>\",\n  \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n  \"context_id\": \"ctx_1773782663367_bj2fyhb\",\n  \"scan_type\": \"observability_scout\",\n  \"category\": \"<category>\",\n  \"title\": \"<title>\",\n  \"description\": \"<description>\",\n  \"reasoning\": \"<reasoning>\",\n  \"effort\": <1-10>,\n  \"impact\": <1-10>,\n  \"risk\": <1-10>,\n  \"goal_id\": \"<goal_id_if_matched>\"\n}\n```\n\n**IMPORTANT:** Always include effort, impact, and risk scores (1-10) for every idea. Do NOT leave these fields empty or null.\n\n### Field Requirements\n\n**category** (string): One of:\n- `functionality`: New features, missing capabilities, workflow improvements\n- `performance`: Speed, efficiency, memory, database, rendering optimizations\n- `maintenance`: Code organization, refactoring, technical debt, testing\n- `ui`: Visual design, UX improvements, responsiveness\n- `code_quality`: Security, error handling, type safety, edge cases\n- `user_benefit`: High-level value propositions, business impact, user experience\n\n**title** (string, max 60 chars): Clear, specific, action-oriented title\n\n**description** (string): 2-4 sentences explaining:\n- What the idea is\n- How it would be implemented\n- What problem it solves\n\n**reasoning** (string): 2-3 sentences explaining:\n- Why this idea is valuable\n- What impact it will have\n- Why now is a good time to implement it\n\n**effort** (number 1-10) - Total cost to deliver: time, complexity, people, and coordination overhead:\n- 1-2 = Trivial (few hours to a day, single file/config change, no coordination)\n- 3-4 = Small (few days, localized to one module, minimal testing)\n- 5-6 = Medium (1-2 weeks, multiple components, requires thoughtful testing)\n- 7-8 = Large (several weeks to a month, spans multiple services, requires coordination)\n- 9-10 = Massive (multi-month initiative, dedicated team, new architecture)\n\n**impact** (number 1-10) - Business value, user satisfaction, and strategic alignment:\n- 1-2 = Negligible (nice-to-have, no measurable user/business outcome)\n- 3-4 = Minor (quality-of-life for small user subset, weak strategy alignment)\n- 5-6 = Moderate (clear benefit to meaningful segment OR solid OKR alignment)\n- 7-8 = High (strong user impact across significant portion of base, clear competitive/revenue implication)\n- 9-10 = Critical (existential for product success, major revenue driver, transformational work)\n\n**risk** (number 1-10) - Probability and severity of things going wrong:\n- 1-2 = Very safe (well-understood change, easily reversible, no security/data/compliance surface)\n- 3-4 = Low risk (minor uncertainty, limited blast radius, standard rollback possible)\n- 5-6 = Moderate (some technical unknowns OR touches sensitive area like payments/auth/PII)\n- 7-8 = High (significant uncertainty, depends on external systems, potential user-facing regression)\n- 9-10 = Critical (novel/unproven approach, hard to reverse, major outage/data loss potential)\n\n**goal_id** (optional string): If the idea relates to one of the project goals listed above, include the goal ID\n\n## Example Workflow\n\n```bash\n# Step 1: Create scan record\n# NOTE: Use node -e or grep/sed to parse JSON — do NOT use jq or python (may not be installed)\nSCAN_RESPONSE=$(curl -s -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/scans \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\n    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n    \"scan_type\": \"claude_code_observability_scout\",\n    \"summary\": \"Claude Code idea generation - Observability Scout\"\n  }')\n\n# Extract scan_id from response (cross-platform — no jq/python required)\nSCAN_ID=$(node -e \"console.log(JSON.parse(process.argv[1]).scan.id)\" \"$SCAN_RESPONSE\")\n\n# Step 2: Create ideas using the scan_id\ncurl -X POST http://localhost:3000/api/ideas \\\n  -H \"Content-Type: application/json\" \\\n  -d '{\n    \"scan_id\": \"'$SCAN_ID'\",\n    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n    \"context_id\": \"ctx_1773782663367_bj2fyhb\",\n    \"scan_type\": \"observability_scout\",\n    \"category\": \"functionality\",\n    \"title\": \"Example: Add user session caching layer\",\n    \"description\": \"Implement Redis caching for user session data to reduce database queries. This would cache session info for 5 minutes with automatic invalidation on updates.\",\n    \"reasoning\": \"Currently every page load queries the session table. This adds latency and database load. Caching would reduce DB calls by ~70%.\",\n    \"effort\": 5,\n    \"impact\": 7,\n    \"risk\": 4\n  }'\n```\n\n## Execution Steps\n\n**Phase 1: Analyze the \"personas-cloud\" project**\n1. Read the project's CLAUDE.md or AI.md documentation if available\n2. Explore the codebase structure, focusing on the context files\n3. Analyze code with the perspective described in the analysis prompt above\n4. Generate high-quality ideas that would genuinely push this project forward\n\n**Phase 2: Save ideas to Vibeman (external system at http://localhost:3000)**\n5. Create a scan record via curl to http://localhost:3000/api/scans\n6. Save each idea via curl to http://localhost:3000/api/ideas using the scan_id\n7. Report what ideas were created\n\n**REMINDER:** Do NOT create any files or endpoints in \"personas-cloud\". Only READ/ANALYZE it.\n\n## Error Handling\n\n**CRITICAL:** If Vibeman API calls fail (4xx/5xx errors), follow these rules:\n- **DO NOT** attempt to debug, fix, or investigate Vibeman's database, schema, or code\n- **DO NOT** look for database files, read migration files, or inspect Vibeman's source code\n- **DO NOT** install tools like jq, python, or sqlite3 — they are not needed\n- If a curl call fails, log the error response and try adjusting the JSON payload (e.g., remove optional fields like `detailed`, `provider`, `model`)\n- If it still fails after one retry, report the error and move on to the next idea\n- Vibeman is an EXTERNAL system — you have no ability or responsibility to fix it\n\n## Quality Standards\n\n- **Be Specific**: Reference actual files, components, or patterns you observed\n- **Be Actionable**: Ideas should be clear enough to implement without further clarification\n- **Be Valuable**: Focus on ideas that bring real improvement, not busywork\n- **Match Goals**: If an idea aligns with a project goal, include the goal_id\n- **Avoid Duplicates**: Check the existing ideas section and don't suggest similar items\n\n## Output\n\nAfter completing the task, summarize:\n- How many ideas were created (saved to Vibeman at http://localhost:3000)\n- Brief list of idea titles\n- Any observations about the \"personas-cloud\" codebase\n\n**Final Checklist:**\n- [ ] I analyzed the \"personas-cloud\" codebase (READ ONLY)\n- [ ] I did NOT create any new files in \"personas-cloud\"\n- [ ] I saved ideas via curl to Vibeman's API at http://localhost:3000\n- [ ] Each idea has effort, impact, and risk scores (1-10)\n","numLines":440,"startLine":1,"totalLines":440}}}
