[2026-03-18T18:09:58.437Z] [STDOUT] {"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_012jnumvkw2dADLqhn4TopeM","type":"tool_result","content":"[\n  {\n    \"id\": \"cc3c8a86-5043-41c3-8b05-27185b65aa1d\",\n    \"scan_id\": \"867ef7ee-0524-4331-b44f-093ad9a7977e\",\n    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n    \"context_id\": null,\n    \"scan_type\": \"tech_innovator\",\n    \"category\": \"functionality\",\n    \"title\": \"Causal correlation chains across audit events\",\n    \"description\": \"Add a correlation_id and parent_event_id to audit_events, threading a causal chain through related operations. When an execution starts, generate a correlation ID that flows through worker:connected, key:decrypt, execution completion, and worker:disconnected. The AuditPolicy.attach() method and direct record() calls in dispatcher.ts and httpApi.ts would propagate correlation context. This dissolves the structural constraint that audit events are isolated rows with no causal relationship � today, correlating a key:decrypt_failed with the worker:connected that triggered it requires manual timestamp-range searches across unstructured detail fields.\",\n    \"reasoning\": \"Forensic investigation of security incidents in multi-tenant credential systems requires answering: which execution triggered this decryption, which worker ran it, what happened after the failure? Currently this requires manually correlating timestamps across independent rows with unstructured detail strings. Causal chains make incident investigation O(1) instead of O(n). The compounding value is that every new audited action automatically participates in existing chains, making the forensic graph richer over time without additional engineering effort.\",\n    \"status\": \"pending\",\n    \"user_feedback\": null,\n    \"user_pattern\": 0,\n    \"effort\": 8,\n    \"impact\": 9,\n    \"implemented_at\": null,\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-03-18T12:33:38.958Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-03-18T12:33:38.958Z\",\n    \"requirement_id\": null,\n    \"goal_id\": null,\n    \"risk\": 7,\n    \"provider\": null,\n    \"model\": null,\n    \"detailed\": 0,\n    \"context_color\": null\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": \"af8b3c58-e4b4-4fae-9321-aaf32e82fcc7\",\n    \"scan_id\": \"1eaf3f6b-6f66-4dbc-a9a0-81a85c760238\",\n    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n    \"context_id\": null,\n    \"scan_type\": \"observability_scout\",\n    \"category\": \"functionality\",\n    \"title\": \"Add event-to-execution correlation tracing\",\n    \"description\": \"Thread the originating eventId through to the ExecRequest object (add an optional eventId field to the ExecRequest type in types.ts) and persist it in the persona_executions table. This creates a bidirectional link: from any execution you can trace back to its triggering event, and from any event you can find all executions it spawned. Log both IDs together at dispatch time.\",\n    \"reasoning\": \"Currently, when a user reports a broken execution, developers must manually correlate execution logs with event logs using timestamps and persona IDs � error-prone and slow. A direct eventId to executionId link enables instant root-cause tracing: was the event malformed? Was the subscription misconfigured? Was the persona at capacity? This is the single highest-leverage debug improvement for the event bus.\",\n    \"status\": \"implemented\",\n    \"user_feedback\": null,\n    \"user_pattern\": 0,\n    \"effort\": 4,\n    \"impact\": 9,\n    \"implemented_at\": \"2026-03-18T17:42:19.253Z\",\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-03-18T12:01:08.197Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-03-18T17:53:35.708Z\",\n    \"requirement_id\": \"idea-af8b3c58-add-event-to-execution-correla\",\n    \"goal_id\": null,\n    \"risk\": 3,\n    \"provider\": null,\n    \"model\": null,\n    \"detailed\": 0,\n    \"context_color\": null\n  },\n  {\n    \"id\": \"7f85b0cd-2316-4e84-8ca4-e681db702e13\",\n    \"scan_id\": \"28393e86-6455-4da9-a7b0-2d6abac9948c\",\n    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n    \"context_id\": null,\n    \"scan_type\": \"observability_scout\",\n    \"category\": \"maintenance\",\n    \"title\": \"Add request correlation IDs to HTTP handler\",\n    \"description\": \"Generate a unique request ID (nanoid) at the top of each HTTP request in httpApi.ts and attach it to a child pino logger (logger.child({ reqId })). Pass this child logger to all downstream operations. Include the request ID in error responses so users can reference it in support requests. This threads a single identifier through all log entries for a given request.\",\n    \"reasoning\": \"When the catch block at httpApi.ts:366 logs an error, it only includes the URL. There is no way to correlate that error with the specific persona, tenant, or sequence of operations that led to it. Request IDs are the foundation of production traceability and pino already supports child loggers natively.\",\n    \"status\": \"implemented\",\n    \"user_feedback\": null,\n    \"user_pattern\": 0,\n    \"effort\": 3,\n    \"impact\": 8,\n    \"implemented_at\": \"2026-03-18T17:42:50.222Z\",\n    \"created_at\": \"2026-03-18T11:51:20.693Z\",\n    \"updated_at\": \"2026-03-18T17:42:50.222Z\",\n    \"requirement_id\": \"idea-7f85b0cd-add-request-correlation-ids-to\",\n    \"goal_id\": null,\n    \"risk\": 1,\n    \"provider\": null,\n    \"model\": null,\n    \"detailed\": 0,\n    \"context_color\": null\n  }\n]","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"346ea655-cc50-41aa-a6e5-8b6b2130a050","uuid":"c8575dab-a5fd-4207-80db-15e680dfda26","timestamp":"2026-03-18T18:09:58.359Z","tool_use_result":{"stdout":"[\n  {\n    \"id\": \"cc3c8a86-5043-41c3-8b05-27185b65aa1d\",\n    \"scan_id\": \"867ef7ee-0524-4331-b44f-093ad9a7977e\",\n    \"project_id\": \"c6fd0474-19f1-4223-b6a9-752077c51d3d\",\n    \"context_id\": null,\n    \"scan_type\": \"tech_innovator\",\n    \"categor